This paper deals with game theory and optimization problems, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of cs.GT (Game Theory and Mechanism Design). The paper also involves the analysis of equilibria and strategies, which are relevant to the subfield of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper discusses the ability of players to approximately play equilibrium strategies, which is a topic in the subfield of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of equilibrium concepts and bounds on the price of anarchy are also relevant to the subfields of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics).
